Scalable Webserver Infrastructure using AWS

Project Description

This project involves creating a scalable, highly available web server infrastructure using AWS services. The infrastructure is designed to handle dynamic traffic loads with autoscaling, load balancing, and custom domain configuration through Route 53. It also includes the use of a custom Amazon Machine Image (AMI) to ensure consistent server configurations.

Project Steps

1. Create a Linux-based webserver

  • Launch an EC2 instance with a Linux AMI (e.g., Amazon Linux 2, Ubuntu).
  • Install and configure a web server (e.g., Apache or Nginx).
  • Test the web server by hosting a sample website.

2. Create an AMI (Amazon Machine Image)

  • Create a AMI from the configured web server instance.

  • Actions

  1. Go to the EC2 console, select the instance, and choose Create Image to create an AMI.
  2. Provide a name and description for the AMI.
  3. AWS will save the AMI, which can be used to launch identical servers in the future.

3. Delete the Webserver

  • Terminate the manually created EC2 instance after creating the AMI.

4. Create an Autoscaling Group

  • Set up an autoscaling group using the custom AMI.
  • Define scaling policies based on CPU utilization.
    • Set a threshold for CPU utilization (e.g., launch a new instance if CPU > 70% or terminate an instance if CPU < 30%).
  • Configure minimum, maximum, and desired number of instances.

5. Create a Load Balancer

  • Create an Application Load Balancer (ALB).
  • Configure the load balancer to distribute traffic across instances. "port 80 (HTTP)"
  • Create a target group and register the autoscaling groups instances as targets
  • Attach the autoscaling group to the load balancer.



6. **Configure a Custom Domain with Route 53

Objective: Map a custom domain to the load balancer using Route 53.

Actions:
1. Register a domain name in Route 53 or use an existing one.
2. Create a hosted zone for the domain in Route 53.
3. Add an A record (Alias) in the hosted zone that points to the load balancers DNS name.
4. Verify that the custom domain resolves to the load balancer, and accessing it loads the web application hosted on the servers.



Test the application by accessing it through the custom domain.

Tools and Services Used

  1. Amazon EC2: For hosting the web server.
  2. Amazon Machine Image (AMI): To create a reusable image of the web server.
  3. AWS Autoscaling: To scale instances dynamically based on traffic.
  4. Application Load Balancer (ALB): To distribute incoming traffic.
  5. Route 53: For custom domain mapping and DNS management.
  6. Linux Commands: For configuring the server environment.

Expected Outcome

  • A scalable web server infrastructure that automatically adjusts to traffic demands.
  • A custom domain that resolves to the load balancer and serves the hosted application.
  • High availability and consistent server configurations using AMI and autoscaling.
